I had high hopes for
the one we did with you, Gary--

01:59.610 --> 02:02.788
The 1715 Fleet--
I really did, you know?

02:02.872 --> 02:05.374
How many stories have you
told us about walking the beach

02:05.458 --> 02:07.543
and finding this
and finding that?

02:07.702 --> 02:10.129
I-I really thought that
we were gonna pull something

02:10.288 --> 02:12.798
out of the, out of
the beach sand, I really did.

02:12.882 --> 02:14.291
Yeah, it has that feeling.

02:14.384 --> 02:16.293
I mean,
your treasure hunting chances

02:16.386 --> 02:18.554
on the Treasure Coast can
actually change

02:18.638 --> 02:22.382
on the tides from day to day.

02:22.466 --> 02:24.801
This is it, guys.
Treasure central.

02:24.886 --> 02:27.229
NARRATOR:
Early in 2021,

02:27.388 --> 02:30.807
Rick, Marty and Matty
traveled to Sebastian, Florida

02:30.900 --> 02:33.393
to help Gary Drayton
look for valuables

02:33.477 --> 02:36.980
related to the historic
1715 Treasure Fleet.

02:37.064 --> 02:38.991
- Oh, look at that color green.
- Yep.

02:39.075 --> 02:40.734
- (chuckles)
- Come on!

02:40.818 --> 02:43.328
Look at that.
That is fantastic.

02:44.247 --> 02:46.740
NARRATOR:
Encompassing 12 galleons,

02:46.824 --> 02:49.326
the Treasure Fleet set sail
from the Spanish port of Havana

02:49.410 --> 02:53.172
on July 24, 1715,

02:53.331 --> 02:56.258
carrying billions
in plundered gold, silver

02:56.342 --> 02:58.668
and precious jewels
back to Spain.

02:58.753 --> 03:00.503
But on July 31,

03:00.597 --> 03:03.682
11 of the 12 ships
were destroyed

03:03.841 --> 03:06.009
when the fleet was caught
in a massive hurricane

03:06.102 --> 03:08.937
just off the coast of Florida.

03:09.096 --> 03:13.609
JOHN D.: When the ships sailed
from Havana on the 24th of July

03:13.693 --> 03:15.360
everything went okay
for the first few days

03:15.519 --> 03:18.113
and then,
the oceans start rolling,

03:18.272 --> 03:20.115
and big swells start coming in.

03:20.200 --> 03:22.692
The pilots realized that

03:22.785 --> 03:25.787
they were gonna be in
for a big storm.

03:25.872 --> 03:27.197
- (lightning crashing)
- ROB W.: And one by one,

03:27.281 --> 03:28.949
the ships get smashed to pieces

03:29.042 --> 03:31.368
against the reefs of Florida.

03:31.461 --> 03:35.797
700 to 1,000 people died
in the initial shipwreck.

03:35.957 --> 03:38.208
More perished in the weeks
that came from starvation,

03:38.301 --> 03:39.301
and they didn't have
fresh water.

03:39.385 --> 03:41.553
The news got to Havana first.

03:41.638 --> 03:43.555
The governor sent help
immediately,

03:43.714 --> 03:46.049
and they sent salvage divers
right away.

03:46.142 --> 03:49.052
That operation lasted
for three years,

03:49.136 --> 03:51.230
and they actually were very,
very successful

03:51.389 --> 03:53.473
in recovering
a lot of the treasure.

03:53.566 --> 03:56.318
NARRATOR: Although the
Spanish were able to recover

03:56.402 --> 03:58.987
as much as two thirds
of the sunken cargo,

03:59.146 --> 04:01.731
billions in valuables remained,

04:01.824 --> 04:03.492
which generations
of treasure hunters

04:03.651 --> 04:05.661
have been salvaging ever since.

04:07.080 --> 04:10.573
Gary, who has lived in the area
and combed the beaches

04:10.658 --> 04:13.001
for more than 20 years
with his metal detecting gear,

04:13.086 --> 04:16.672
has discovered
more than $1 million in treasure

04:16.831 --> 04:18.999
that continually washes
onto shore,

04:19.092 --> 04:22.844
including a 22 and a half carat
gold and emerald ring.

04:25.172 --> 04:26.506
That's why you called us
there, right? To say, like,

04:26.599 --> 04:28.258
this is something
we can immediately make a find.

04:28.351 --> 04:30.185
Oh, yeah.
I wanted to give these guys

04:30.270 --> 04:33.105
- instant treasure hunting gratification.
- (chuckles)

04:33.264 --> 04:35.098
Uh, I was hoping
that we could find,

04:35.191 --> 04:37.434
uh, friends of "my precious."

04:37.527 --> 04:39.111
(chuckles)

04:39.195 --> 04:42.022
All it takes is
one turn of the shovel

04:42.115 --> 04:45.951
to change your fortunes
and make history as well.

04:46.035 --> 04:47.861
Well, there's a third thing,
too, Gary,

04:47.945 --> 04:49.195
about that particular trip.

04:49.289 --> 04:50.956
Had we found something--

04:51.115 --> 04:52.949
As long as you stayed
in the sand, right?

04:53.034 --> 04:54.534
Wasn't that the rule?--
You got to keep it.

04:54.627 --> 04:56.953
Do you remember,

04:57.038 --> 04:59.289
from our last trip with Gary
to his backyard,

04:59.382 --> 05:01.207
do you remember John Brandon?

05:01.301 --> 05:02.968
-Oh, very much so.
-Absolutely. How do you forget that?

05:03.052 --> 05:05.137
- (Matty chuckles)
- He of the 80-pound silver bar.

05:05.221 --> 05:07.389
-Almost gave me a hernia. Yeah. Yeah.
-MATTY: Bingo.

05:07.548 --> 05:09.891
Well, John and his team
just renewed

05:09.976 --> 05:11.885
- their salvage license.
- Okay.

05:11.969 --> 05:13.219
And they're about to embark
on their new season.

05:13.304 --> 05:14.938
That's cool.
That's really cool.

05:16.724 --> 05:19.809
NARRATOR: Having grown up on
Florida's so-called Treasure Coast,

05:19.902 --> 05:22.571
John Brandon has been diving
on the shipwrecks

05:22.655 --> 05:26.649
of the 1715 Fleet since he was
a teenager in the 1960s,

05:26.734 --> 05:28.151
when he was first hired

05:28.235 --> 05:30.653
by renowned treasure hunter
Mel Fisher.

05:30.747 --> 05:32.664
JOHN B.: One day,
when I was 13 years old,

05:32.823 --> 05:34.499
I went over to
a neighborhood friend's house,

05:34.584 --> 05:37.160
and Mel was there
with a big find of treasure

05:37.244 --> 05:38.995
they had just made off Vero.

05:39.080 --> 05:42.341
And that really got me,
uh, hooked.

05:42.500 --> 05:45.752
I actually asked, uh, Mel Fisher
for a job that day.

05:45.845 --> 05:47.754
But because I was 13,
it was one of these,

05:47.847 --> 05:49.839
"Go away, kid, you're
bothering me" kind of things.

05:49.932 --> 05:52.517
When I was 17 years old,
I'd already found

05:52.602 --> 05:56.012
hundreds of silver coins
on the beach after big storms.

05:56.097 --> 05:59.524
I'd found a number of gold coins
and a lot of artifacts.

05:59.609 --> 06:01.267
Then Mel finally hired me.

06:01.361 --> 06:04.279
Outside of his own sons,
I was the youngest person ever

06:04.364 --> 06:07.440
to captain, uh,
one of his treasure boats.

06:07.533 --> 06:11.194
NARRATOR: Even though that
company salvaged hundreds of tons

06:11.287 --> 06:14.039
in gold, silver
and jewels themselves,

06:14.123 --> 06:18.201
today, John Brandon serves
as the operations manager

06:18.285 --> 06:22.464
for the 1715 Fleet-Queens
Jewels, LLC--

06:22.623 --> 06:24.207
The entity which controls

06:24.300 --> 06:26.876
all legal salvage rights
to the wrecks.

06:28.629 --> 06:30.797
- JOHN B.: This is part of what you guys are looking for.
- RICK: Oh, yeah.

06:30.890 --> 06:32.882
NARRATOR: During their
recent search with Gary

06:32.967 --> 06:34.643
along Florida's Treasure Coast,

06:34.802 --> 06:39.055
Rick, Marty and Matty
were fascinated and intrigued

06:39.140 --> 06:41.233
by some of John's
greatest discoveries.

06:41.392 --> 06:42.984
MARTY: That is really
cool, John. Wowzer.

06:43.144 --> 06:44.644
And the gold shines forever.

06:44.728 --> 06:46.062
They came off the bottom
of the ocean

06:46.147 --> 06:47.897
looking just like that.

06:48.908 --> 06:53.495
John has told me that
they have a virgin area,

06:53.579 --> 06:56.665
unsearched, in the ocean
off the coast,

06:56.749 --> 06:59.918
right in the heart of
the 1715 Spanish Treasure Fleet.

07:00.077 --> 07:02.337
And he says, "I don't get
excited about things.

07:02.496 --> 07:03.913
I'm excited about this one."

07:03.998 --> 07:05.924
Well, he clearly knows
what he's doing, John Brandon.

07:06.083 --> 07:08.001
- Yes.
- I mean, he's a very interesting guy.

07:08.094 --> 07:10.587
Well, he's actually standing by
if you'd like to talk to him.

07:10.680 --> 07:12.589
I'd love to.
Let's talk to him again.

07:12.673 --> 07:13.840
Let's go back
to the Treasure Coast.

07:13.933 --> 07:15.016
MARTY:
Yeah, excellent.

07:17.178 --> 07:18.511
- MARTY and RICK: Hello, John.
