13:10.614 --> 13:12.791
within that debris field that
might lead us to the treasure.

13:12.875 --> 13:16.702
Here's a gold coin
off the 1715 Fleet.

13:16.787 --> 13:19.288
- May I? (groans) - The gold
comes up shining just like that.

13:19.373 --> 13:23.468
The silver coins become
encrusted through sulfiding

13:23.627 --> 13:25.711
and seashells and things
will stick to them.

13:25.796 --> 13:27.972
But that's the kind of items
that we're gonna be looking for

13:28.057 --> 13:29.474
out there today with Greg.

13:29.633 --> 13:31.976
Wow. Let's go find
some treasure.

13:32.135 --> 13:34.729
♪ ♪

13:36.974 --> 13:38.566
NARRATOR: Later that
morning, Matty and John arrive

13:38.725 --> 13:40.985
at Captain Hiram's Marina,

13:41.144 --> 13:43.479
where they will join
Captain Greg Bounds

13:43.572 --> 13:45.731
and their team to search
for a debris field

13:45.816 --> 13:50.570
believed to be connected to
the 1715 Spanish Treasure Fleet.

13:50.663 --> 13:52.655
MATTY: Gentleman,
how are you? Matty Blake.

13:52.739 --> 13:55.083
- Matty. George Friedel.
- George, good to meet you, sir.

13:55.167 --> 13:57.159
-Ric Harshman.
-Ric, great to meet you. Thanks for having us.

13:57.244 --> 13:58.578
JOHN B.: Matty, these are
the principals

13:58.671 --> 14:00.496
of the 1715 Fleet-Queens Jewels.

14:00.581 --> 14:02.173
These are the guys
that own the company.

14:02.258 --> 14:04.175
John said there's gonna be
a pile of gold out there.

14:04.334 --> 14:06.168
- (laughter)
- JOHN B.: A whole pile.

14:06.262 --> 14:07.428
I think if there's not
a pile of gold,

14:07.588 --> 14:09.097
they're gonna make me
swim back to the docks,

14:09.256 --> 14:10.682
- so we better find something.
- Yeah.

14:10.766 --> 14:12.183
I-I assume you guys didn't

14:12.342 --> 14:14.427
get into this
because you liked fishing.

14:14.520 --> 14:15.937
I mean, this is about treasure,
right, at the end of the day?

14:16.021 --> 14:18.180
-Exactly.
-It's about treasure. That's right.

14:18.265 --> 14:21.693
There's tremendous quantities of
treasure that's still out there.

14:21.852 --> 14:25.697
We conservatively estimate
at least $750 million

14:25.856 --> 14:28.274
- in registered silver and gold.
- (chuckles)

14:28.358 --> 14:29.692
Now you want to know
why we're out here?

14:29.776 --> 14:32.028
- (laughter)
- I just saw four eyes light up.

14:32.112 --> 14:33.538
Let's get out there
and find some treasure.

14:33.622 --> 14:35.832
- JOHN B.: Sounds great.
- (seagulls squawking)

14:37.877 --> 14:40.369
- Hey. Good morning, Greg.
- Hey, John. Welcome board.

14:40.454 --> 14:42.213
- Very good to see you.
- Good to see you.

14:42.372 --> 14:44.132
This is Matty.
This is Captain Greg.

14:44.216 --> 14:45.633
- Nice to meet you. Good.
- Matty Blake. How are you?

14:45.792 --> 14:47.302
How about any safety issues?

14:47.386 --> 14:48.878
- Anything like that to be aware of?
- Well, you know,

14:48.962 --> 14:50.379
weather can change at any time.

14:50.464 --> 14:52.214
This is one of
the most dangerous inlets

14:52.299 --> 14:54.216
on Florida's coast,
so we got to be careful.

14:54.310 --> 14:55.810
The tides change, and they-- if
they're a little bit of swell,

14:55.895 --> 14:57.386
it can stand the waves right up,

14:57.479 --> 14:59.063
so we got to be careful
for that.

14:59.148 --> 15:00.899
- Let's go find something, get on the ocean. Done.
- Sounds good.

15:00.983 --> 15:03.234
All right, guys,
let's go, throw them off.

15:07.406 --> 15:08.489
MATTY:
Here we go.

15:08.649 --> 15:10.316
What we came here for, baby.

15:10.409 --> 15:13.578
What's most exciting is,
this is virgin territory.

15:13.737 --> 15:16.989
And it's kind of outside
where they believed

15:17.074 --> 15:19.667
the 1715 Spanish Treasure Fleet
was wrecked.

15:19.752 --> 15:23.079
If it's period, that's
the 1715 Spanish Treasure Fleet,

15:23.163 --> 15:25.831
and that's a new site
in a new area.

15:25.925 --> 15:27.425
That's history making.

15:29.678 --> 15:32.505
All right, fellas.
We got to set our anchors here.

15:32.598 --> 15:34.840
So, walk me through that, John.
What's he doing right now?

15:34.925 --> 15:37.101
He's getting ready to run out
one of the stern anchors,

15:37.186 --> 15:39.595
and he's gonna use that whaler.
He's gonna take off in a minute,

15:39.680 --> 15:41.430
and that line's gonna go
shooting out of

15:41.523 --> 15:43.024
that little hole right there.

15:43.108 --> 15:44.859
- MATTY: There he goes.
- JOHN B.: There he goes.

15:44.944 --> 15:47.103
So, he's actually pulling it out
to where they want it?

15:47.187 --> 15:48.863
JOHN B.: So now he's, now
he's pulling the stern anchor out.

15:49.022 --> 15:51.199
And when Chas gets in position,

15:51.283 --> 15:53.409
he'll wave his arms,
and Chas will drop the anchor.

15:54.695 --> 15:56.287
MATTY:
Ah, there he goes.

15:57.623 --> 16:00.032
NARRATOR: Before
the divers enter the water,

16:00.117 --> 16:02.868
the team will clear
the thick layer of sand and silt

16:02.962 --> 16:05.955
from their target area
utilizing a method invented

16:06.048 --> 16:10.042
in the 1960s by
legendary salvager Mel Fisher.

16:10.127 --> 16:12.595
Coming in gear.
All right, let's dig a hole.

16:14.965 --> 16:18.384
NARRATOR: Using two
33-inch-wide steel tubes,

16:18.468 --> 16:20.478
known as mailbox blowers,

16:20.562 --> 16:23.648
the boat's engine wash
is redirected downward,

16:23.732 --> 16:25.474
creating a powerful dredge

16:25.567 --> 16:27.727
that can easily clear
the ocean bottom

16:27.820 --> 16:29.737
some 30 feet underwater.

16:32.733 --> 16:34.233
How are we doing on our target?

16:34.317 --> 16:35.484
We're right on
a big target here.

16:35.577 --> 16:36.411
- MATTY: Ooh!
- There's a little bit

16:36.495 --> 16:37.737
more mass to it.

16:37.830 --> 16:39.163
This target looks very exciting.

16:39.322 --> 16:40.748
All right, let's get them
in the water.

16:40.907 --> 16:41.749
- What do you think, captain?
- All right, let's do it.

16:41.834 --> 16:43.626
♪ ♪

16:52.419 --> 16:54.095
MATTY:
Captain's in.

16:54.179 --> 16:56.931
♪ ♪

17:01.845 --> 17:03.771
You got that bin ready
for all the new finds?

17:03.856 --> 17:04.939
- (chuckles): Yeah.
- All right.

17:05.024 --> 17:06.348
It's all ready.
Everything's set.

17:06.442 --> 17:07.692
We just need to bring up
the treasure.

17:11.864 --> 17:13.781
Mike, test,
test if you're ready?

17:17.119 --> 17:18.119
I got you, Mike.

17:41.393 --> 17:42.560
RIC: Okay, we got
something coming up.

17:47.316 --> 17:49.150
- JOHN B.: Got the target?
- I need a knife.

17:49.234 --> 17:50.401
- JOHN B.: Oh, you need a knife.
- Yep.

17:54.481 --> 17:57.158
Well, they just came up
for a dive knife down there,

17:57.242 --> 18:00.078
and they can use that to kind of
make spots in the mud.

18:00.162 --> 18:01.821
There's a layer of
hard-packed mud down there,

18:01.905 --> 18:03.656
and the magnetometer target
is actually

18:03.749 --> 18:05.416
in that base material.

18:05.575 --> 18:07.493
If he wants a knife,
that means they're on it, right?

18:07.577 --> 18:08.920
JOHN B.: Yeah, that means
they've got something, and again,

18:09.004 --> 18:10.663
they can't dig it up
with their hands,

18:10.747 --> 18:11.881
so they needed to get a tool
down there.

18:17.262 --> 18:18.429
They definitely have the target,

18:18.514 --> 18:19.922
so let's hope
it's from the wreck

18:20.015 --> 18:21.590
and plays
into the scatter pattern

18:21.675 --> 18:23.017
- that-that we've been working on.
- MATTY: Great.

18:30.776 --> 18:32.351
All right, that sounds great.
So, you've got eyes on them?

18:32.444 --> 18:33.402
They're on the target?

18:39.368 --> 18:40.442
All right.

18:40.527 --> 18:41.869
MATTY:
Come on, baby.

18:49.962 --> 18:52.380
NARRATOR: Just off the coast
of Sebastian, Florida,

18:52.539 --> 18:55.967
Matty Blake, along with
treasure salvager John Brandon

18:56.126 --> 18:58.627
and his team, are working
to recover artifacts

18:58.712 --> 19:01.714
and valuables
on a possible shipwreck

19:01.798 --> 19:05.059
from the famed
1715 Spanish Treasure Fleet.

19:08.138 --> 19:09.889
Do you see the object
they're working on?

19:09.973 --> 19:12.316
Have they pulled anything out?
What's it look like? What shape?

19:27.166 --> 19:29.909
All right, so we're
getting targets, that's great.

19:29.993 --> 19:33.495
We have documented fact,

19:33.580 --> 19:37.091
1715 Treasure Fleet went down
in this area,

19:37.176 --> 19:40.094
and we know that these ships had
hundreds and hundreds

19:40.253 --> 19:42.513
of millions of dollars,
perhaps billions of dollars,

19:42.672 --> 19:44.515
worth of gold, silver
and treasure on them.

19:44.674 --> 19:47.268
That's a fact,
so you're not hunting

19:47.352 --> 19:49.437
for some mysterious,
nebulous thing.

19:49.521 --> 19:50.688
You know there's treasure
in these waters.

19:50.772 --> 19:52.348
Diver's coming up.

19:52.432 --> 19:53.941
Let's just hope
it's something good.

19:55.352 --> 19:56.936
MATTY: There's a part
of the ship right there.

19:57.020 --> 19:59.697
I hope. Look at this.

20:01.366 --> 20:03.609
- Oh, I'll tell you what it is.
- What?

20:03.693 --> 20:05.119
This is an iron ring.

20:05.204 --> 20:06.621
It would have come up like this.

20:06.705 --> 20:08.789
And this iron ring would have
come up here

20:08.874 --> 20:10.616
for a rope to run through it.

20:10.700 --> 20:11.784
And it definitely looks
like it's period.

20:11.868 --> 20:12.710
- Ah, yes.
- I mean, definitely looks like

20:12.794 --> 20:14.787
it's from the wreck.

20:14.871 --> 20:16.455
- This piece would be into the hull of the boat.
- Into the ship.

20:16.548 --> 20:18.624
Then probably exit
a piece of wood in here

20:18.708 --> 20:20.292
- because it would chafe and break.
- Right.

20:20.385 --> 20:22.887
They're starting to bring up
those pieces.

20:22.971 --> 20:24.639
Looks like a hammer.

20:24.723 --> 20:26.224
That looks more typical of a...

20:26.383 --> 20:27.391
- Spike. Yeah.
- of a ship's spike.

20:28.727 --> 20:30.728
But it definitely looks
like period material.

20:30.887 --> 20:32.230
Yeah, we're definitely
finding that debris.

20:32.389 --> 20:34.065
JOHN B.: It looks
good. It looks really good.

20:35.817 --> 20:36.984
MATTY: Well, yeah,
it's always described as--

20:37.143 --> 20:38.394
The night of that storm,
right?--

20:38.478 --> 20:40.479
We say, like,
the ships literally got

20:40.572 --> 20:43.741
blown apart into pieces,
and we're pulling up pieces.

20:43.900 --> 20:45.743
♪ ♪

20:49.498 --> 20:51.749
Got another interesting piece.

20:51.833 --> 20:53.334
Oh, wow. Look at that.

20:53.418 --> 20:55.086
JOHN B.:
Yep, a large ship's pin.

20:55.245 --> 20:56.754
RIC: Yeah, that
looks like a large pin.

20:56.838 --> 20:59.173
NARRATOR: After
finding three large artifacts

20:59.258 --> 21:03.252
potentially connected
to the 1715 Treasure Fleet...

21:03.336 --> 21:06.013
- Can almost see the heads.
- John Brandon and the team have good reason to believe

21:06.172 --> 21:09.767
they're getting closer to
the millions in gold and silver

21:09.926 --> 21:12.436
that may still lie
scattered nearby.

21:13.847 --> 21:16.691
So, uh, when I got to the
bottom, the viz was--

21:16.775 --> 21:19.443
I'm gonna estimate--
About five feet.

21:19.528 --> 21:22.938
- The artifacts are penetrated down into that shell and clay.
