Damn straight, I remember
the big bar of silver.

25:42.290 --> 25:44.124
My back still hurts.

25:44.209 --> 25:45.867
Well, I'm hoping after tomorrow
I'll be able to show you

25:45.952 --> 25:47.202
something real similar.

25:47.295 --> 25:49.129
I certainly hope so,
Matty Blake.

25:49.289 --> 25:50.297
Get back after it.

25:50.382 --> 25:51.873
Thanks, fellas.

25:51.958 --> 25:53.208
- Talk to you soon.
- MARTY: Best of luck.

25:53.293 --> 25:54.468
- See ya. Stay safe.
- Good luck, Matty.

25:54.553 --> 25:55.627
Good luck, mate.

25:55.712 --> 25:56.971
MATTY:
Cheers, guys.

26:03.136 --> 26:05.980
NARRATOR: As a new day begins
in Sebastian, Florida...

26:06.139 --> 26:07.806
- MATTY: Good morning, team.
- GREG: Hey, good morning, Matty.

26:07.890 --> 26:08.974
- How you doing this morning?
- How you guys doing?

26:09.058 --> 26:10.976
Matty Blake once again joins

26:11.060 --> 26:13.395
treasure salvager John Brandon
and his team.

26:13.479 --> 26:14.905
So, what's the plan for today?
What you got?

26:15.064 --> 26:16.148
GREG:
So, where we were yesterday,

26:16.241 --> 26:17.733
we had a lot of targets.

26:17.817 --> 26:19.243
And so, I want to
keep following this trail

26:19.402 --> 26:20.736
- and see what else is on it.
- JOHN B.: Very good.

26:20.820 --> 26:23.372
Let's go get it.
Let's go get it. All right.

26:24.916 --> 26:26.908
NARRATOR:
They are continuing their search

26:26.993 --> 26:29.003
in a previously unexplored area

26:29.162 --> 26:31.255
for wreckage connected to

26:31.339 --> 26:34.666
the famed
1715 Spanish Treasure Fleet,

26:34.759 --> 26:39.171
which may be hiding millions
in lost gold and silver.

26:39.255 --> 26:40.756
MATTY: Day two, you
know, they're ready to go.

26:40.849 --> 26:42.591
I'm definitely ready to go.

26:42.684 --> 26:44.518
I think we're all
very encouraged

26:44.603 --> 26:47.271
by what was found yesterday
in just a short dive.

26:47.355 --> 26:48.930
GREG:
It looks like we're pretty good.

26:49.015 --> 26:50.357
JOHN B.:
It looks real good. Right on it.

26:50.442 --> 26:52.276
Today's the day.

26:52.360 --> 26:53.777
GREG:
All right, let's dig a hole.

26:53.862 --> 26:55.771
(chain links clicking)

26:55.864 --> 26:58.198
NARRATOR:
Having reached their target area

26:58.283 --> 27:00.951
and anchored the salvage boat...

27:01.036 --> 27:04.538
- Going in gear.
- Captain Greg Bounds once again employs

27:04.623 --> 27:08.700
the high-powered mailbox blowers
to clear the silt and sand

27:08.785 --> 27:10.619
from the ocean bottom below,

27:10.712 --> 27:13.455
so the divers can begin
their search.

27:13.548 --> 27:15.957
GREG: All right, Matty, we're
over, uh, "big boy" target here.

27:16.042 --> 27:17.635
There's a little bit
more mass to it

27:17.719 --> 27:19.053
- than what we got yesterday.
- All right, we like that.

27:19.137 --> 27:21.555
So, we should uncover it
on our first hole.

27:21.640 --> 27:23.131
All right, let's get 'em
in the water.

27:23.216 --> 27:24.800
- What do you think, Captain?
- All right, let's do it.

27:24.893 --> 27:26.310
JOHN B.:
Find something.

27:31.641 --> 27:33.484
♪ ♪

27:44.829 --> 27:46.830
(detector beeping)

27:56.249 --> 27:57.257
All right, so we're
getting targets.

27:57.342 --> 27:59.134
That's great.

28:16.102 --> 28:17.194
All right great,
see you on the surface.

28:17.278 --> 28:18.696
Great, great, over.

28:18.855 --> 28:21.115
♪ ♪

28:21.274 --> 28:22.700
Oh, yeah, look at that!

28:24.527 --> 28:26.203
Yep.

28:26.287 --> 28:28.029
GREG: Looks like some
rigging pieces of some sort.

28:28.123 --> 28:29.531
Could this be a blunderbuss?

28:29.615 --> 28:31.032
-(laughter) -JOHN B.:
No, they all-- looks like...

28:31.117 --> 28:32.710
It's kind of in the shape
of a blunderbuss.

28:32.869 --> 28:33.877
They all look
like ship's spikes.

28:33.962 --> 28:36.380
(overlapping chatter)

28:36.464 --> 28:38.132
This is probably
the head of the spike,

28:38.291 --> 28:39.708
the tail, all of these.

28:39.801 --> 28:40.959
But they all look
like they could

28:41.043 --> 28:42.553
very well be period material

28:42.637 --> 28:44.796
- from the 1715 Fleet wreck.
- That's good. That's good.

28:44.889 --> 28:46.298
JOHN B.: This is excellent.
This is a great find.

28:46.391 --> 28:48.967
It looks like Captain Greg
has put us on the trail.

28:49.060 --> 28:51.562
Any ballast stones
or anything else down there?

28:51.721 --> 28:52.730
No, I didn't see no ballast
or anything.

28:52.814 --> 28:54.973
- Didn't get any other real hits.
- Okay.

28:55.057 --> 28:56.391
Well, we've got a lot more
in here to dig up.

28:56.484 --> 28:57.642
Let's get to the next spot.

28:57.727 --> 28:58.902
GREG:
Okay. Let's move on over.

29:00.739 --> 29:03.815
NARRATOR: In order to track the
debris field of the possible wreck,

29:03.900 --> 29:06.985
Captain Greg and his team
are now adjusting

29:07.078 --> 29:09.913
their anchor lines
in order to reposition the boat

29:09.998 --> 29:12.249
over the next
nearby target area.

29:12.333 --> 29:13.500
MATTY:
Oh, so you're just swinging it.

29:13.585 --> 29:15.502
- Yeah.
- I thought you were gonna get up there

29:15.661 --> 29:17.504
- and drive it over, but you're just... I see.
- No, no, no, no.

29:17.663 --> 29:19.840
- Wow.
- Usually all we have to do is anchor one time for the day,

29:19.999 --> 29:22.092
- and then we move the boat wherever we need to move it to.
- Incredible.

29:22.177 --> 29:23.927
It's a great system.

29:30.009 --> 29:31.101
Divers are wet.

29:33.262 --> 29:35.180
Is this normally
how it kind of goes?

29:35.264 --> 29:37.107
You-you start following
these bread crumbs,

29:37.192 --> 29:39.351
this-this trail,
and then you hit gold?

29:39.435 --> 29:40.435
JOHN B.: It's putting
all the clues together.

29:40.528 --> 29:42.446
On the shipwreck the<i> Atocha,</i>

29:42.530 --> 29:44.698
we followed a debris field
for eight linear miles.

29:44.783 --> 29:47.701
- Wow.
- And yet it led to $500 million worth of treasure.

29:47.786 --> 29:49.787
♪ ♪

30:08.056 --> 30:10.808
-GREG: You got something big? You need a rope?
-Yeah.

30:13.728 --> 30:15.053
MATTY: All right,
the rope's in the water.

30:15.137 --> 30:17.648
Are they, are they acquiring
the target now?

30:27.400 --> 30:28.992
I see it, I see it.

30:30.245 --> 30:32.496
MATTY:
Wow. Look at that.

30:34.073 --> 30:36.083
GREG:
Whew.

30:36.242 --> 30:39.503
-Look at that bad boy.
-MATTY: Look at that. Incredible.

30:40.672 --> 30:43.498
What are you thinking?

30:43.583 --> 30:45.676
Well, it's kind of difficult
to tell right now.

30:45.760 --> 30:48.929
Probably the best guess is
it's a ring off a spar,

30:49.013 --> 30:50.514
off one of the crossbeams
on the galleon.

30:52.934 --> 30:55.510
NARRATOR:
On early 18th-century galleons,

30:55.603 --> 30:58.188
spar rings were fitted around

30:58.273 --> 31:01.349
the horizontal cross members
attached to masts.

31:01.434 --> 31:04.695
They secured the rigging
that controlled a ship's sails.

31:06.272 --> 31:08.356
- MATTY: Tag it and bag it.
- GREG: Whoa! Hold up, hold up!

31:08.441 --> 31:10.442
We've got more!

31:10.535 --> 31:11.869
JOHN B.:
Whoa.

31:12.028 --> 31:13.036
Wow.

31:14.873 --> 31:17.207
Look at that.

31:17.292 --> 31:19.117
Man, oh, man.

31:19.210 --> 31:21.536
Is it a little bit smaller
than the other one?

31:21.621 --> 31:22.954
It's definitely smaller
than the other one.

31:23.039 --> 31:25.048
So, it's like steps
going down the spar,

31:25.133 --> 31:27.134
- as it gets smaller and smaller, you know?
- MATTY: Got it. Okay.

31:27.218 --> 31:29.636
You couple this
with the three iron spikes

31:29.721 --> 31:31.129
that were found
a little bit earlier,

31:31.213 --> 31:32.547
you can't get clues any better
than that.

31:32.632 --> 31:34.049
I mean, that's what
you're out here looking for.

31:34.133 --> 31:35.392
The only other clues you get
that are better

31:35.476 --> 31:36.894
is if you actually
find the treasure

31:36.978 --> 31:38.645
- in the hole.
- MATTY: I love it.

31:38.730 --> 31:41.306
♪ ♪

31:41.390 --> 31:43.567
GREG:
My interpretation is that

31:43.651 --> 31:45.560
a good section of the ship
came through there,

31:45.645 --> 31:47.812
because these big iron pieces
of the ship--

31:47.906 --> 31:50.324
And spikes and pins--
They don't just float out there.

31:50.408 --> 31:52.826
They have to be connected
to large pieces of the ship.

31:52.911 --> 31:54.411
Digging the hole.

31:54.495 --> 31:57.322
GREG: And that could
carry gold and silver,

31:57.415 --> 31:59.583
and other items like that,
that we're really after.

32:01.077 --> 32:02.077
- MATTY: Let's go.
- GREG: All right, let's do it.

32:02.161 --> 32:04.087
Still on the boat?
Come on, let's go.

32:20.855 --> 32:23.357
JOHN B.:
That's a big squall there.

32:23.516 --> 32:25.433
We're gonna get dumped on.

32:25.526 --> 32:28.111
RIC:
It's closing in quick.

32:29.939 --> 32:32.032
- You want to get 'em up?
- Yeah, let's get 'em up.

32:32.116 --> 32:34.368
Hey, Mike, the winds are kicking
up here on the surface,

32:34.452 --> 32:36.244
so let's end this dive. Surface.

32:39.365 --> 32:41.116
(thunder crashes, rumbles)

32:41.200 --> 32:42.584
CHAS: This can be
some serious (bleep) here.

32:47.048 --> 32:48.548
RIC:
We got to get out of here.

32:48.633 --> 32:50.467
NARRATOR: Just off the coast
of Sebastian, Florida...

32:50.551 --> 32:52.961
- GREG: Matty, help go get this anchor.
- MATTY: All right.

32:53.045 --> 32:56.223
an approaching storm
has suddenly caused

32:56.307 --> 32:57.882
the experienced crew
of the<i> Capitana</i>

32:57.976 --> 33:00.227
to call a halt to their search

33:00.311 --> 33:02.721
for millions in sunken treasure.

33:02.805 --> 33:05.983
Pull that anchor up.

33:06.067 --> 33:07.976
- You get it? All right.
- (straining): Got it.

33:08.060 --> 33:10.821
Storm came up like that.
(snaps fingers)

33:10.905 --> 33:13.073
The sky got dark.
You felt like someone put on

33:13.157 --> 33:14.315
an air conditioner
all of a sudden.

33:14.400 --> 33:15.316
We were all hot,
then all of a sudden

33:15.401 --> 33:16.234
were all freezing cold.

33:16.327 --> 33:17.828
Yeah, that's a nasty--

33:17.912 --> 33:19.913
Look at that rain.

33:19.998 --> 33:22.833
MIKE N.: We got to get this other
anchor up without getting electrocuted.

33:24.585 --> 33:27.170
MATTY: When an
experienced sailor tells you,

33:27.255 --> 33:28.997
"We have to move right now

33:29.081 --> 33:30.841
or we're in danger of getting
electrocuted,"

33:30.925 --> 33:32.175
I'm off the water.

33:32.260 --> 33:33.677
(thunder rumbling)

33:33.761 --> 33:35.137
That's nasty.

33:38.683 --> 33:40.508
JOHN B.: You want to get
out before it gets really bad.

33:40.593 --> 33:42.093
We're trying to put a diver
under the water,

33:42.186 --> 33:44.187
to unpin the blowers,

33:44.272 --> 33:45.680
and the blowers are going
up and down.

33:45.765 --> 33:47.932
You want to have
all the anchors on board,

33:48.017 --> 33:49.851
the blowers up,
all your crew on board,

33:49.935 --> 33:51.945
everybody's safe,
and start going for the inlet.

33:52.030 --> 33:53.688
And it can get very, very rough,

33:53.773 --> 33:55.949
and it can get very,
very dangerous.

33:56.034 --> 33:58.368
- (thunder rumbles)
- MATTY: Oh, geez!

33:59.704 --> 34:01.780
JOHN B.:
Let's get back to the dock.

34:01.864 --> 34:05.283
There's no amount of treasure
that's worth a person's life.

34:05.367 --> 34:06.960
Let's face it, okay?

34:07.045 --> 34:08.712
So, when we see
bad weather coming in

34:08.796 --> 34:10.371
and lightning coming in
like this,

34:10.465 --> 34:12.632
you know,
it's time to pull up anchor

34:12.792 --> 34:14.551
and let's get out of here.

34:19.557 --> 34:21.382
GREG: I'm real
confident about the work

34:21.467 --> 34:22.967
that we're doing out there.

34:23.052 --> 34:24.552
We're finding parts
and pieces to this ship

34:24.637 --> 34:26.730
where nobody's ever
dreamed it would be.

34:26.814 --> 34:29.316
I think it's gonna lead us
to-to something even bigger.

34:29.400 --> 34:31.651
- (thunder rumbling) - MATTY:
Weather's coming, so it was a good call.

34:31.736 --> 34:35.146
-It was a good call we came in.
-Yeah, wow. We got out just in time,

34:35.239 --> 34:38.316
but you guys and the whole team
did an incredible job.

34:38.409 --> 34:40.902
Every time you're at a target
that you wanted to be,

34:40.995 --> 34:42.412
when you were
where you wanted to be,

34:42.497 --> 34:45.415
you guys brought something up,
so that's great.

34:45.500 --> 34:46.917
I mean, that's a good sign
you're on the debris field.

34:47.076 --> 34:49.002
And it looks like it is material
from the 1715 Fleet.

34:49.087 --> 34:50.578
MATTY:
That wasn't scrap metal.

34:50.663 --> 34:52.506
Hey, let's follow
that trail to gold.

34:52.590 --> 34:53.998
RIC:
Great job.

34:54.083 --> 34:55.509
- Hey, thank you so much...
- GREG: Yes, sir.

34:55.593 --> 34:57.252
(chatter fades)

34:57.336 --> 34:59.513
- (thunder rumbling)
- (lightning crashes)

35:07.271 --> 35:08.429
MATTY: They use this
tri-anchor system.

35:08.514 --> 35:10.014
You'll be watching
live time to target

35:10.099 --> 35:11.274
on a screen, and literally,

35:11.433 --> 35:12.859
"Okay, we're on it.
Uh, move it over here.

35:12.944 --> 35:14.519
Okay, we're on it,"
then blow it.

35:14.603 --> 35:15.854
It was thrilling, actually,

35:15.938 --> 35:17.105
to pull those large artifacts
on the boat.

35:17.189 --> 35:18.857
But they weren't shiny
and they weren't gold,

35:18.941 --> 35:20.784
so I was a little disappointed.

35:20.868 --> 35:23.870
It's not necessarily always
about the gold and silver.

35:23.955 --> 35:26.698
It's about what you pull out.

35:26.782 --> 35:28.533
What story does it tell?

35:28.617 --> 35:31.628
And John documented everything,

35:31.712 --> 35:33.788
and I-I applaud that.

35:33.873 --> 35:36.708
Well, I also know that
there's been an update.

35:36.801 --> 35:39.886
- Oh.
- And-- Yeah, and he's actually standing by.

35:39.971 --> 35:41.212
- Let's talk to him again.
- All right.

35:41.297 --> 35:42.380
MARTY:
Excellent.

35:42.473 --> 35:43.890
- Hello, John.
- RICK: John.

35:43.975 --> 35:45.550
- GARY: Hello, mate.
<i>- Hey, guys,</i>

35:45.643 --> 35:46.560
<i>good to talk with you again.</i>

35:46.719 --> 35:48.645
<i>This is, uh, Captain Mike Perna</i>

35:48.729 --> 35:50.564
who's with me today,

35:50.648 --> 35:53.558
who's got many years of finding
treasures and artifacts.

35:53.642 --> 35:55.226
- Hello, Mike.
- (others shouting salutation)

35:55.319 --> 35:56.561
Pleasure to meet you.

35:56.645 --> 35:58.897
Well, John I was just
filling the guys in here

35:58.981 --> 36:00.490
on my adventures
on the Treasure Coast--

36:00.575 --> 36:02.734
How exciting it was to be
on the boat,

36:02.818 --> 36:06.913
to watch you operate, to finally
see those blowers in action,

36:06.998 --> 36:09.082
to talk about Mel Fisher
and the history

36:09.241 --> 36:11.084
and to pull up
those finds that we made,

36:11.243 --> 36:13.170
uh, were really exciting.

36:13.254 --> 36:14.996
Well, we really enjoyed
having you, uh, down here.

36:15.080 --> 36:17.999
I know that Captain Greg
was definitely impressed

36:18.083 --> 36:19.918
<i>by all the work you did.</i>

36:20.011 --> 36:22.921
And he's sorry we didn't
bring up any gold or silver,

36:23.005 --> 36:26.341
<i>but shortly after Matty left,
Mike made a big discovery</i>

36:26.425 --> 36:28.852
to the south of where we had
Matty out on the wreck.

36:29.937 --> 36:31.479
Well, we found treasure.

36:37.937 --> 36:39.938
<i>JOHN B.: There's only been
two significant finds</i>

36:40.031 --> 36:41.948
<i>of worked silver</i>

36:42.107 --> 36:43.524
on the 1715 Fleet--

36:43.618 --> 36:45.535
One of which
I made back in 1982.

36:45.694 --> 36:48.029
<i>But Mike here just made
a very significant find</i>

36:48.122 --> 36:50.698
of very ornate pieces of silver.

36:50.783 --> 36:52.951
<i>Shortly after Matty left,</i>

36:53.035 --> 36:54.953
<i>- unfortunately.</i>
- (chuckles) - (groans)

36:55.046 --> 36:56.371
Sorry, Matty.

36:56.455 --> 36:57.872
- Just missed a treasure boat.
- Oh, man.

36:57.965 --> 36:59.874
MARTY:
Got any pictures of those?

36:59.967 --> 37:02.293
We have some of
the actual items, uh,

37:02.386 --> 37:03.962
that Mike found,

37:04.046 --> 37:05.388
<i>and I'll hand some over to Mike</i>

37:05.473 --> 37:06.890
<i>and let him explain
what they are.</i>

37:07.049 --> 37:10.143
- Fantastic.
<i>- MIKE P.: Here we have</i>

37:10.302 --> 37:12.812
a piece of silver that we're
not exactly sure what it is.

37:12.897 --> 37:15.315
<i>It's definitely a plate
of some sort.</i>

37:15.399 --> 37:19.978
On the back you'll notice
there's a threaded nut here.

37:20.071 --> 37:21.396
<i>I don't know if you guys
can see that at all.</i>

37:21.480 --> 37:22.405
- Yeah. Oh, yeah.
- RICK: Yeah.

37:22.490 --> 37:24.148
And so, we're not sure--

37:24.233 --> 37:25.742
This would affix to something.

37:25.901 --> 37:27.652
And, uh,
what makes the most sense is

37:27.736 --> 37:29.153
it's possibly something
that would've been

37:29.247 --> 37:30.830
maybe a leather strap
or something like that.

37:30.915 --> 37:32.165
That somebody would've worn
here.

37:32.250 --> 37:34.668
♪ ♪

37:34.752 --> 37:36.670
And what it depicts is
a mounted horseman here.

37:36.754 --> 37:38.162
<i>And I don't know if you can see
down at the bottom.</i>

37:38.256 --> 37:40.006
- MATTY: Yeah. Now I see it.
- MARTY: Oh, yeah.

37:40.091 --> 37:42.250
MATTY:
A horse. Yeah, yeah, yeah. Wow.

37:42.334 --> 37:44.511
JOHN B.: It obviously
was a very important piece.

37:44.670 --> 37:45.837
In my entire time working

37:45.921 --> 37:47.430
<i>in the 1715 Fleet shipwreck--</i>

37:47.515 --> 37:49.090
<i>So, over 55 years--</i>

37:49.174 --> 37:51.768
I've never seen a piece,
uh, even similar to that.

37:51.927 --> 37:53.353
I knew I should've delayed
my flight.

37:53.437 --> 37:54.604
MARTY:
Yeah, you should've stayed.

37:54.763 --> 37:56.523
Yeah. You just missed
the treasure boat.

37:56.607 --> 37:57.691
- Oh, my God.
- MARTY: Look at that.

37:57.850 --> 37:59.693
So this piece is in fact silver,

37:59.777 --> 38:02.362
but it's also, uh...
has a gold wash on it.

38:02.446 --> 38:03.521
<i>I don't know
if you guys can tell,</i>

38:03.605 --> 38:06.941
Uh, it appears to depict
the Madonna.

38:07.026 --> 38:08.785
- MATT: Wow.
- MARTY: Yeah. - Yeah.

38:08.869 --> 38:10.370
<i>JOHN B.:
It's a magnificent piece</i>

38:10.454 --> 38:12.697
because they didn't have
gold-plating back in 1715,

38:12.781 --> 38:15.283
They would actually dip items
in molten gold

38:15.376 --> 38:17.702
<i>to put a gold sheen on them.</i>

38:17.786 --> 38:19.045
And that's
what's been done to this.

38:19.130 --> 38:20.714
A very, very impressive piece.

38:20.798 --> 38:22.540
- (Matty groaning)
- MARTY: Very cool piece.

38:22.624 --> 38:24.384
- It's unbelievable.
